The soil is dark and not hard, to the depth of a foot, and overlays a rich, red clay. There are lofty trees everywhere, except where the land has been cultivated by a few persons. Numerone springs furnish a supply of water. No animals are seen except decr, beavers and squirrels, which are as large as the hares of Europe. There is an 'infinite number of birds of various colors, sneh as engles, craueS, swanS, goese, partridges and ducks. From these facte, it is inferred that the country is not without such things, as contribute to the prosperity or pleasure of those, who inhabit it.

There is no subscription to the extracts made by Father William McSherry.
